(5, 'What, why, how, where and who for property investors', 'In the early years in my 20’s at university, property investment had never occurred to me at all', '<div class="paragraph" style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px 0px 20px; font-family: Lato, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5em; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); text-align: justify; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">In the early years in my 20&rsquo;s at university, property investment had never occurred to me at all. I have always thought; I&rsquo;ll go through university, get a job and I should be employable until I am 65 years when I reach retirement. The 45 years of study and work should be no problem to me at all. Don&rsquo;t get me wrong, working and studying are the best part of life as there is so much to learn and they really make your brain consistently work and on the move. However, flexibility began to be an issue when I developed a passion for traveling. Working in Australia, the average annual leave days are 20 and when I worked in the UK, it is 25; then the thought of moving back to Australia down back to 20 again wasn&rsquo;t something I prefer. I want more!<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThat is when I realised something had to be done so I can reduce my working hours and still be on the same salary/income. That is when I learnt about passive income, which basically means, making money without really physically working for it. Passive income can be made using investment models such as equity/shares, currency, properties, futures, etc. I then began reading the news and understand the world of finance (coming from an engineering background), then the numbers became really interesting. However, from the various investment models, I found only property investment is controllable. Equity, currency, futures (etcetera) ; all depends on the world&rsquo;s economy, government fiscal policies, government/federal affairs, environmental factors and the list goes on. Property investment has smaller risks (once you have invested) and especially; risks can be controlled. For instance, for those who are thinking property prices fluctuate as much as share prices. Yes you are right, they fluctuate due to economic cycles, but the fluctuation is steadier and can be controlled. Landlords can decide to sell the house when they identify the cycles, and prices will not stall quickly as share prices would if the stock market is falling &ndash; we can take the Chinese stock market in 2015 as an example.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nBy now you are probably thinking to yourself, how you would get started in the property market. Despite where you are living in the world, the general idea of property investment is very similar:<br />\r\n<br />\r\n1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; You buy a property (house, apartment, commercial building, land etc) with an idea of:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span style="background-color:initial">&nbsp;You rent it out to service your mortgage and possibly make a small profit from the difference of rent and mortgage. If you have enough money to purchase the property, then the rental is all yours.</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="background-color:initial">You wait and sell the property for a capital gain.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div style="color: rgb(102, 102, 102); font-family: Lato, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; text-align: justify; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">\r\n<div class="wsite-image wsite-image-border-none " style="position: relative; padding-top: 10px; padding-bottom: 10px; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-align: center;"><img alt="Picture" src="http://www.linkedproperties.net/uploads/5/8/2/3/58235949/4688718_orig.jpg" style="border-color:initial; border-image:initial; border-style:initial; border-width:0px !important; max-width:100%; vertical-align:middle; width:auto" />\r\n<div style="font-size: 14.4px;">&nbsp;</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class="paragraph" style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px 0px 20px; font-family: Lato, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5em; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);"><br />\r\n2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Sales contracts and legal system:<br />\r\n<span style="background-color:initial">Despite where you are buying in the world, they all have their own sales contract and legal system to deal with the purchase. Although they are very similar, some countries have very different methods of legalizing the purchase. The legal documents generally are in the local language; however, if you are an international buyer, they should be able to issue you a copy in English. Make sure you have a legal advisor taking you through the details as the sales contract are always at the interests of the seller and not the buyer. &nbsp;</span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style="background-color:initial">One very good example is buying an off the plan property. There is always an off the plan property you could buy anywhere in the world. With off the plan properties, because they are not structurally or physically built yet, so there are a lot of potential risks. In 2008 during the Global Financial Crisis, many developers could not accrue funds from banking institutions towards their project and hence, caused the property development to stall. This has left many buyers out of pocket and loses their deposits for their property. Good example is property investment in Dubai during this period; as it is illegally in Dubai to not be able to fund your debts, so developers have left the country once they were notified by banks that they could not fund them any further. Therefore, it is wise to ensure you have a sunset clause on the contract. So if the project is not completed on a specific date then you are able to obtain your deposit back. In most countries, deposits are left in a trust account, so it is accessible if the developer doesn&rsquo;t complete.</span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Prospective tenants:<br />\r\nThe property you are interested in may sound very good, but the most important thing for buy to rent for investors is the prospective tenants. There is a variety of good and bad tenants. It is wise to research the area before making your decision on a property. Normally young working classes are ideal tenants as they are young and likely to not afford their own property yet, so they would be willing to rent. However, families are also very stable as they are likely to have their children and will require a place they can stay longer &ndash; so your investment is stable for some amount of time.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIt is important to avoid bad neighbourhoods as it is highly likely your tenants may not keep up to date with your rent. These areas may have a good incentive to purchasing as they are more affordable than better areas, and during growth, these areas will have the highest capital gain return (as you are likely to have purchased them for very cheap). However, do your research before making such assumptions. Some countries such as UK have very long eviction period, so it could lead you months of unpaid rent and ultimately you will be required to pay your mortgage (if you take a mortgage for your property).</div>\r\n\r\n<div style="color: rgb(102, 102, 102); font-family: Lato, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; text-align: justify; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">\r\n<div class="wsite-image wsite-image-border-none " style="position: relative; padding-top: 10px; padding-bottom: 10px; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-align: center;"><img alt="Picture" src="http://www.linkedproperties.net/uploads/5/8/2/3/58235949/1414495_orig.jpg" style="border-color:initial; border-image:initial; border-style:initial; border-width:0px !important; max-width:100%; vertical-align:middle; width:auto" />\r\n<div style="font-size: 14.4px;">&nbsp;</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class="paragraph" style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px 0px 20px; font-family: Lato, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5em; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">Now, buying properties globally is very different as there are the following &lsquo;barriers to entry&rsquo; that you would need to consider and understand:<br />\r\n<br />\r\n1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Government regulation\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Can you own the property free hold or is it leasehold? Free hold is generally you can indefinitely own the property and lease hold is for a limited amount of time. Generally countries with high population density will allow foreigners to purchase the property on lease hold only. This is due to the land being a sovereign to the local people.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Can foreigners buy properties there (if you are a foreigner and considering of buying a property in the country you desire). In countries where land is limited and of high population density tend to have stringent regulation upon this. For instance, in Hong Kong where land is extremely limited; would have hurdles for foreigners to own a property there. You can get away with this if you have lived in the country for some amount of time, or to be employed there or own a business there for an amount of time. Before investing in these countries, you should weigh up the pros and cons of your investment in that country.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Stamp duty or known as property tax. If you are buying a property, tax can hinder your purchasing power as you have to pay extra towards the government&rsquo;s tax, which some perceive as &lsquo;dead money&rsquo;. It is not adding any value to your purchased property but for processing your deeds. Most countries require a stamp duty fee upon your property purchase, in fact; I do not know of any that doesn&rsquo;t require a stamp duty for property purchase. Stamp duty can range from anything 0.5 &ndash; 4% of the property&rsquo;s purchased price. Therefore, it is important to have this calculated in your budge before making an offer.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div style="color: rgb(102, 102, 102); font-family: Lato, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; text-align: justify; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">\r\n<div class="wsite-image wsite-image-border-none " style="position: relative; padding-top: 10px; padding-bottom: 10px; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-align: center;"><img alt="Picture" src="http://www.linkedproperties.net/uploads/5/8/2/3/58235949/1422255_orig.jpg" style="border-color:initial; border-image:initial; border-style:initial; border-width:0px !important; max-width:100%; vertical-align:middle; width:auto" />\r\n<div style="font-size: 14.4px;">&nbsp;</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class="paragraph" style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px 0px 20px; font-family: Lato, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5em; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Finance<br />\r\nFor first home buyers/investors, this is probably the most important barrier to purchasing a property. As I started the property ladder later than I wished I had, I can understand the hurdle of trying to get your foot in the ladder. It comes down with a lot of determination and resilient to saving for the deposit. Living at home is always a good idea as you will be saving on your rental and hence, reduces your monthly expenditures significantly.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nEvery country would have their finance regulations and procedures to the minimum deposit required. In developed countries, minimum deposits range from 20-25%&nbsp; with mortgage interests from 2.5-6%. In developing countries, deposits are a lot higher ranging from 35-40% and mortgage interest up to 10%. As developing countries would have limited funds and high risks for financial institutions to take for investors, so their requirements are higher.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSo once you have your property, this is considered as property investment and you can start making strategic decisions to how you would grow your investment.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSome investors do not enjoy the stress of managing their properties, so they would hire a property management agency to deal with the tenants, contracts and maintenance. However, this will incur a charge, and they can be anywhere from 5-10% of your monthly return.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhen you start investing properties, you will likely to continue to work in your full time profession. You should never consider leaving until you have made financial positive cash flow (if you are looking to buy to rent/lease). I would generally look for the same monthly income as my full time employment before considering of making a move.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nFor typical property deposit from 20-30%, you are likely to make a 5-10% &lsquo;profit&rsquo; from your monthly rental return. This is after mortgage and agency fees and does not include extra fees to maintain the property or strata/management fees (if applicable). Therefore, most successful buy to let investors generally require up to 10 properties before making a good income.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nHowever, there are some very creative investors that make financial gain from buy and sell strategy. Buying an old and run down property, furnishing it to something more desirable and selling it for a profit is quite common. If you decide to do this, you should consider capital gain tax (often in developed countries). Normally the government requires you to be a resident of the property for a minimum of 4-6 months before considering your property as your home, so selling the property shall not incur capital gain tax. Tax for every country is very different, so we probably have to touch base with this on a country portfolio.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThese are a few of advices I can offer for first time buyers for now. Keep posted for further posts!</div>\r\n', NULL, 'blog', 443, '2016-11-18 08:50:53', '2016-12-10 09:36:04', 'true', '/data/image/blog/banner-img1.jpg', 'what-why-how-where-and-who-for-property-investors', 'false', '', 'Trường Khương'),
(6, 'The keys of property investments', 'As this is our first post we would like to introduce some key points about property investments for those that are just starting out in their property ladder', '<div>As this is our first post we would like to introduce some key points about property investments for those that are just starting out in their property ladder. For those that have already started their property investment, may also find this interesting to compare to how your decisions were made.</div>\r\n\r\n<div>Firstly, we would like to share some background information about us so you can understand the geographic locations of our knowledge. We are of British, Australian, Hong Kong and Vietnamese citizens and residents. Therefore, we have strong knowledge in these regions, however, we are always seeking new knowledge and investments from anywhere else. We will share more information about these regions as time passes by.</div>\r\n\r\n<div>As people have always asked, how do property investors make money? As there is no doubt property investors are likely to start off with a huge debt (known as the mortgage), so how do we make money?</div>\r\n\r\n<div>What we have come to realize is people do not like debt and it is perceived as extremely bad and should avoid if you can. We do agree with these people, as they are right, we should always try to avoid debts at all time. However, there are two types of debts; the &#39;good&#39; debts and the &#39;bad&#39; debts. So you might be wondering, why are there such things? Well, good debts are if the debt is spent on an investment that has potential for growth and generate money or income. Bad debts are used to purchase more liabilities that will not in time generate any income or value, but in fact diminish the value from the first day you took on the debt.</div>\r\n\r\n<div>Now, property investments generally give you a financial gain in the long term. It is generally not something that would generate financial benefit in the short term. We would like to explain that there are 2 types of property investments; they are of &#39;capital gain&#39; investments or &#39;high returns&#39; investments.</div>\r\n\r\n<div>Capital gain&nbsp;<br />\r\nCapital gain is considered when the value of your property has gained value over the period of time you have purchased it for. As population growth is inevitable, so in the span of 10 years&rsquo; time, the value of properties generally would have grown due to higher demand for properties to supply to the growing population. The capital gain can be comparable to the purchased price or there could be a significant gain. Significant gains are generally from a &#39;longer&#39; property holding period, as the time you have held it would be enough time for the population to grow.</div>\r\n\r\n<div>To calculate the capital gain, we use the following formula:<br />\r\n(Sold price - purchased price)/(purchased price) x 100 = XX %</div>\r\n\r\n<div>However, when capital gain is achieved through a resale, there may be tax incurred on the &#39;profits&#39; that have been made. &nbsp;This is generally in &#39;developed&#39; countries where proper tax regulations are set up. For the developing countries, this is not necessary.&nbsp;</div>\r\n\r\n<div>For example, in Australia; 50% of the &#39;capital gain&#39; would be included with your annual income salary during tax declaration.</div>\r\n\r\n<div>In countries like Vietnam where it is still developing, there is no such thing as capital gain tax. The capital gains are 100% entitled to the seller. This is one of the main advantageous of diversifying your property investments. However, it is advised you speak to your tax/finance advisers as citizen of certain countries may also have to incur international property gain tax as well.</div>\r\n\r\n<div>High returns<br />\r\nHigh yield generally generates &#39;positive gearing&#39; and this is one of the powerful tools property investors use to generate monthly cash flow. High yield refers to the return on your rental income on your invested property. Generally yields are calculated as:</div>\r\n\r\n<div>(Yearly rental)/(Total property cost) x 100 = XX %</div>\r\n\r\n<div>The return yield should generally be compared to your annual average bank&#39;s interest. If it is lower than the bank&#39;s interest then you are not making a financial return gain. If it is higher than the bank&#39;s interest, then you are making a financial return gain. Generally anything higher than 3% compared to the bank&#39;s interest is considered a very good return. However, this does not take into consideration of your annual maintenance costs to your property.</div>\r\n\r\n<div>How do people make money from their monthly rental returns?<br />\r\nWell, this question depends on how much is your mortgage? If you have a high deposit then your monthly repayments should be below than your rental income. The differences of course, will become your &#39;monthly cash flow&#39;. Generally loans in developed countries have mortgage interests of 3-6%. Mortgage Loans in developing countries can be up to 10% which is considered very high and volatile. The higher interests would mean your repayments to the bank would be higher as most of the repayments are of interests. The mortgage&#39;s term (duration) should also be considered as a tool to reduce your monthly repayments. Most people do not like long loans, however, if you have tenants paying your mortgage, why would you be worried about committing to such a long term? Long term would mean your monthly repayments to be less than shorter term loans. Less repayments would mean you will have a greater &#39;monthly rental income&#39; (after paying the mortgage). However, by receiving a longer term loan would also depend on your age. Most banks would considered you to be retired from 60-65 years of age, therefore, your 30 years mortgage loan would generally be approved if you are from 18-35 years old. Therefore, start young and borrow when you can!</div>\r\n', NULL, 'blog', 443, '2016-12-10 08:52:50', '2016-12-10 09:36:05', 'true', '/data/image/blog/Brown-3_0.jpg', 'the-keys-of-property-investments', 'false', '', 'Trường Khương'),
